title: ah-64d_(revision)_(rick_g_earth)
body:
Character from [i][[Rick G Earth]][/i].

She is a Boeing AH-64E Apache attack helicopter, also known as the Apache Guardian.

She is called an "AH-64D revision" because the AH-64E was previously known as the AH-64D Block III.

[b]NOT[/b] to be confused with other AH-64D characters in the game:
* [[ah-64d (rick g earth)|AH-64D]]
* [[ah-64d (3ath.) (rick g earth)|AH-64D, 3rd Anti-Tank Helicopter Unit]]


h4. Appearance
She has [[long hair|long]] [[black hair]].

She wears [[black-framed eyewear|black-framed]] [[glasses]] and [[headphones around neck]].


h4. Profile
Her introduction [1]

[quote]これも命令？　はぁ。ＡＨ-６４Ｄ改、周りはアパッチ・ガーディアンって呼ぶけど可愛くないから好きじゃない。攻撃ヘリのアパッチって聞いたことない？　その中で、最新仕様のブロック３が私。ＴＣＤＬっていう戦術データの通信システムを搭載してるから、実装している子とはデータのやり取りができるの。無人機だって操れちゃうんだから。でもぜんっぜん積んでる子がいなくて旧式のデータリンクも一緒に搭載しているの。…こんなに便利なんだから標準装備にすればいいのに！　ほんと意味分かんない！[/quote]

[quote]Is that an order? Hahh. I'm AH-64 Kai. Everyone calls me Apache Guardian, but I don't like that 'cause it's not cute. Have you heard of the Apache attack helicopter? Amongst those I'm the latest model, the Block 3.  ＴＣＤＬっていう戦術データの通信システムを搭載してるから、実装している子とはデータのやり取りができるの。無人機だって操れちゃうんだから。でもぜんっぜん積んでる子がいなくて旧式のデータリンクも一緒に搭載しているの。…こんなに便利なんだから標準装備にすればいいのに！　ほんと意味分かんない！[/quote]

She is voiced by Hyo-sei (氷青), full name Yokote Kumiko (横手 久美子).

title: morisato_keiichi
body:
Morisato Keiichi (森里 螢一 Morisato Keiichi) is the protagonist of the "[[Aa Megami-sama|Ah! My goddess]]" series. He starts out as a student of the Nekomi Institute of Technology and a member of the NIT Motor Club, who actually used to live in an all male dorm, along with his senpai and a few more members of his Club. 

One day, as he tries to order takeout, Keiichi accidentally dials the Goddess Relief Office, which causes [[belldandy|Belldandy]] to arrive on Earth. She quickly explains to him that he was chosen by Heavens to be granted a single wish, but Keiichi thinks that the whole thing is an elaborate farce set up by his senpai, and comes up with a joke instead. He more or less wishes her to stay with him forever, and immediately comments about that being a crazy wish, although... Belldandy probably thought otherwise and actually submits this request to Heavens. Being kicked out from the dorm for bringing in a girl (as his friends have no idea of Belldandy's true nature as a goddess), Keiichi finds himself on the streets along with Belldandy, and soon searches for a place for them to stay. From that point on, Belldandy's sisters, as well as a couple more goddesses and even demons show up in his life, and (willingly or not) help him to deepen his bond with Belldandy that eventually nurtures into a proper relationship. 

Voiced by: "Masami Kikuchi":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masami_Kikuchi]

title: kokoro_(vocaloid)
body:
ココロ (Heart)
A song for [[Kagamine Rin]]. By Toraboruta-P (トラボルタP) w/ illustrations and PV by Fukusanbutsu-P (副産物Ｐ).

The song tells a story about a robot (Rin) made by a lonely scientist, but is missing a program unable to be made: a Heart. Some time after her creation, her scientist passes away, leaving her alone for several hundred years. She begins to wonder about her creation and makes a wish. She accesses the files that her creator had left and finally gains a Heart. In the process, she discovers what it's like to be happy and sad. With her new feelings, she gratefully dedicates all of the songs that she sings to her creator. In the end, the miracle robot had a short in her system and could no longer sing. However, she had a smile on her face in her last moments, resembling an angel. - Wiki

* "NicoNico video":http://www.nicovideo.jp/watch/sm2500648
* "YouTube video":http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DxvVR63KAcM

h6. Kokoro/Kiseki (Heart/Miracle) by Jun-P

A popular variation on the song, featuring [[Kagamine Len]] in the role of the professor. It tells the story of how he built her and came to make her future "heart", but he dies long before he can get to see her use it. The true answer song by Torabuta-P, "Sayonara, Arigatou", more or less follows the same plot, but has [[Kamui Gakupo]] in the role of the professor instead.

* "NicoNico video - Len ver":http://www.nicovideo.jp/watch/sm3447671

title: ocelot_(kemono_friends)
body:
A [i][[Kemono Friends]][/i] character. She is one of many "Friends" in Japari Park.

The ocelot ([i]Leopardus pardalis[/i]) is a species of small cat known for being the largest of their genus, which includes the closely related [[margay_(kemono_friends)|Margay]]. Their name is derived from the Nahuatl word refering to the [[jaguar_(kemono_friends)|Jaguar]] ("[i]ōcēlōtl[/i]").

Nocturnal, Ocelot (the Friend) spent her short appearence in the anime [[sleeping]] while being described. Her outfit is the same as most of the small cats (similar to Serval's outfit, although she has a top similar to Jaguar's in the anime). She has short hair except for thin [[low twintails]] as well as particularly strong [[tsurime]].

Often conflated with [[revolver_ocelot|a certain other Ocelot]].

title: trans-am
body:
In the series [[Gundam 00]], it is an inherent feature of the [[GN Drive]] (Tau) that temporarily increases their GN Particle output beyond normal parameters for greatly enhanced combat performance. This is a double-edged sword, because this ability only lasts for a limited time and severely lowers the Mobile Suit's performance afterward -- or worse, destroys the GN Drive Tau equipped on the MS.

It also gives the GN Drive-equipped unit a pink-reddish hue when used, a homage to the urban legend (even in-universe in the UC timeline) that any red mobile suit that [[Char Aznable]] pilots goes three times faster.

title: bass_(beer)
body:
"The Bass Brewery /ˈbæs/ was founded in 1777 by William Bass in Burton-upon-Trent, England. The main brand was Bass Pale Ale, once the highest-selling beer in the UK. By 1877, Bass had become the largest brewery in the world, with an annual output of one million barrels. Its pale ale was exported throughout the British Empire, and the company's distinctive red triangle became the UK's first registered trade mark." [1]

title: sailor_senshi_uniform
body:
The iconic costume worn by the [[Sailor Senshi]] in [[Bishoujo Senshi Sailor Moon]]. Its basic design is comprised of the following, starting from the top:

* [[circlet]]
* [[earrings]]
* [[choker]]
* [[sailor collar]]
* a [[bow]] and [[brooch]] on the chest
* [[white gloves|white]] [[elbow gloves]] (hand gloves for Sailors Uranus and Neptune)
* [[white leotard]] with a [[pleated skirt]] over the waist
* a [[back bow|bow on the back of the waist]]
* any variety of footwear

Each of the Sailor Senshi wear different theme colors and have design variations of the above, but the overall uniform is generally the same.

Due to them wearing skirts, it's not immediately obvious that they are wearing leotards. Because of this, images where the leotard can be seen from under the skirt usually get tagged as [[white panties]] due to Danbooru's policy of "tag what you see".

Note that this uniform represents Earth's Sailor Senshi, while warriors from different star systems like the Sailor Starlights and Shadow Galactica have completely different designs, with the sailor collar being the only consistent design aspect.

h4.See also

* [[List of Uniforms]]

title: mareg_(grandia)
body:
A playable character in [[Grandia II]].

An intimidating-looking but good-natured beastman who is seeking vengeance against [[ryudo (grandia)|Ryudo]]'s brother [[melfice (grandia)|Melfice]] for the destruction of his home village. He insists upon [[tio (grandia)|Tio]] joining the party and mentors her on what human emotions are.

title: ryudo_(grandia)
body: The main hero of [[Grandia II]], a sarcastic warrior who is charged with protecting [[elena (grandia)|Elena]]. He had a difficult youth and doesn't like talking about it, but is forced to encounter his older brother [[melfice (grandia)|Melfice]] during their journey.

title: elena_(grandia)
body:
A playable character in [[Grandia II]].

A songstress of Granas who is suddenly possessed by the Wings of Valmar during a ritual where she should have sealed them. She alternates between herself and the Wings' persona, [[Millenia (Grandia)|Millenia]], and they can talk to each other via mirrors, which frustrates Elena to no end. Her journey becomes harder and harder on herself, which has the sardonic [[Ryudo (Grandia)|Ryudo]] grow concerned for her welfare.

title: millenia_(grandia)
body:
A playable character in [[Grandia II]].

The personification of the Wings of Valmar, who possesses [[Elena (Grandia)|Elena]] and occasionally switches bodies with her, especially when fighting Valmar's other body parts. She is seductive and playful, and enjoys teasing Elena, but comes to learn what it is like to be human.

title: the_hurt_locker
body:
[i]"The rush of battle is a potent and often lethal addiction, for WAR IS A DRUG..."[/i] - Chris Hedges. [i]War is the Force That Gives Us Meanning[/i]. 2002.

[b]The Hurt Locker[/b] is a 2008 American war film about a three-man Explosive Ordnance Disposal ([[bomb]] disposal) team during the Iraq War. 

The film was directed by Kathryn Bigelow and the screenplay was written by Mark Boal, a freelance writer who was embedded as a journalist in 2004 with a U.S. Army EOD team in Iraq.

Because the film was not released in the United States until 2009, it was eligible for the 82nd Academy Awards, where it was nominated for nine Academy Awards. It won six Oscars, including Best Director for Bigelow (the first woman to win this award) and Best Picture. Boal won for Best Original Screenplay. 

The Hurt Locker earned numerous awards and honors from critics' organizations, festivals and groups, including six BAFTA Awards. However, it also received criticism by some in the [[military]] for various inaccuracies.

title: juuouki
body:
獣王記 ([i]Juuou-ki[/i], lit. [i]"Beast King's Chronicle"[/i]) is a 1988 beat'em up arcade [[video game]] developed and manufactured by [[Sega]]. Its North American title is [b]Altered Beast[/b].

The primary designer was "Uchida Makoto":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Makoto_Uchida , also responsible for the creation of the first [[Golden Axe]] game.

The game is set in Ancient Greece, and follows a beastman warrior [JP version] / centurion [EN version] who is unsealed/resurrected by Zeus to rescue his daughter Athena, and to do so becomes able to turn into beasts such as a magical [[werewolf]] with the use of power-ups to fight against legions of monsters and the undead. 

After its initial arcade release, it was ported to several home video game consoles and home computers, most notably the [[Sega Master System]] and the [[Sega Mega Drive]], for which it was a pack-in game. The Mega Drive version has been ported into the [[Nintendo 3DS]] as "”3D Juuouki”":http://archives.sega.jp/3d/juouki/ in 2013.

For its 2005 [[Playstation 2]] remake with a more [[science_fiction|sci-fi]] setting, use [[Juuouki ~PROJECT ALTERED BEAST~]] tag.

h4.Characters

There are some name differences between the Japanese and the English version

* [i]Juu-Senshi[/i] (Beastman Clan Warrior) [JP] / Resurrected [[centurion_(juuouki)|centurion]] [EN]
** [[Werewolf]]
** [[Weredragon]]
** [[Werebear]]
** [[Weretiger]]
** Gold werewolf [JP] / [[Golden Werewolf]] [EN]

* [[athena (juuouki)|Athena]]
* [[zeus (juuouki)|Zeus]]

* Nameless Demon [JP] / [[Neff]] [EN]
** Haggar [JP] / [[Aggar]] [EN]

** [[Mouldy Snail]]
** [[Fatty Crocodile]] [JP] / Crocodile Worm [EN]

title: aerial_root
body:
Root that develop from a location on a plant above the surface of the earth or water, as from a stem. They either pass for some distance through the air before reaching the soil or remain hanging in the air and can serve different purposes (for support, breathing air or propagating...)

They are commonly seen in "screw pine":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pandanus], "banyan":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Banyan], "mangrove":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mangrove], etc.
